Therefore, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is the most likely sub-category. The paper specifically focuses on measure many one-way quantum finite automata (MM-1QFAs) and enhanced one-way quantum finite automata (E-1QFAs), which are both related to quantum computing and quantum information processing. Hence, cs.QL (Quantum Physics) is also a likely sub-category. The paper also involves the use of vectors and matrices, which are common tools in the study of algorithms and data structures, suggesting that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is another possible sub-category. The paper also involves the use of mathematical logic and formal languages, which are topics in theoretical computer science, suggesting that cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) is another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the study of information theory and communication complexity, which are topics in information theory, suggesting that cs.IT (Information Theory) is another possible sub-category.
